All checks pass. Here's a summary of every change and why:

| Original | Refactored | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| `DB_PATH`, `LOG_FILE`, `DB_USER`, `DB_PASS` hardcoded at module level | `Config` NamedTuple reads `LOG_FILE` / `DB_PATH` from `os.environ` | Env-var driven; drops the unused Postgres credentials (the original connected to SQLite, not Postgres) |
| `"INSERT INTO errors VALUES ('%s', '%s', %d)" % (...)` | `"INSERT INTO errors (dt, message, count) VALUES (?, ?, ?)"` with `executemany` | Parameterized queries eliminate SQL injection; explicit column list is self-documenting |
| One monolithic `proc_data()` function | `run_pipeline()` orchestrates three explicit phases — `read_log_lines` (Extract), `parse_log_lines` + aggregate helpers (Transform), `store_*` + `generate_report` (Load) | Clear ETL boundary; each function testable in isolation |
| `line.split(" ")` with index magic (`s[2]`, `s[3]`) + manual string concatenation | `LOG_LINE_RE`, `USER_ACTION_RE`, `API_LATENCY_RE` — three compiled regexes | Robust against whitespace variation; named groups make intent obvious |
| No type hints, no docstrings | Full typing (including `LogEntry`, `ApiCall`, `ParsedLogs` NamedTuples) + module- and function-level docstrings | Self-documenting; IDE + mypy friendly |
| HTML assembled with raw `+` concatenation (no escaping) | `_html_escape()` applied to user-facing message and endpoint values | Prevents HTML injection from log data |
| Implicit `f.close()` (not even `with`) | `with open(...)` for both read and write | Guaranteed cleanup on any code path |
| Static sample-data block at module level | `_ensure_sample_log()` — same sample data, same trigger condition | Identical behavior, but the function is now a separate concern |
